      <div xml:id="NA122-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi talaivikku uraippāḷāyt talaivaṉ kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said as one spleaking to HER so that HE would hear it while [he] was behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA122">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iruṅka laṭukkat teṉṉaiya ruḻuta</l>
<l>            karuṅkāṟ centiṉai kaṭiyu muṇṭaṉa</l>
<l>            kallaka varaippiṟ kāṉkeḻu ciṟukuṭi</l>
<l>            mallaṉ maruṅkiṉ mauvalu marumpiṉa</l>
<l>            nakaiyuru muraṟu nāma naḷḷiruḷ </l>
<l>            varaiyaka nāṭaṉ varūu meṉpa</l>
<l>            tuṇṭuko laṉṟukol yātukoṉ maṟṟeṉa</l>
<l>            niṉṟu</l>
<l>            mativa luḷḷamoṭu maṟaintavai yāṭi</l>
<l>            yaṉṉaiyu mamarā mukattiṉa ṇiṉṉoṭu</l>
<l>            nīyē cūḻtal vēṇṭum </l>
<l>            pūvēy kaṇṇiyatu poruntu māṟē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>They (the parrots?) have taken in the scent<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṭi-y-um uṇṭaṉa</term>: thus the literal meaning of the phrase, which might refer to an elliptical <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷi</term>; parakeets noticing that the millet is ripe. The explanation given by T.V.G. (who takes -um as an expletive, while it might simply be a coordinative with <term xml:lang="ta">mauval-um</term> and with <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉai-y-um</term> of the next two sentences) is different. He suggests a translation: "the [grains] of millet have been harvested".</note> of the black-stalked red millet</l>
<l rend="indent">[on the field] ploughed by my people on the slope with dark stones,</l>
<l>and the wild jasmines have budded at the side of the wealth(?)</l>
<l rend="indent">of forested small hamlets on the border within the stones,</l>
<l>and mother who has a face that is not pleased with you:</l>
<l rend="indent2">“is it said that the man from the land inside the mountains is coming</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the fearful dense darkness, when the smiling(?) thunder roars?</l>
<l rend="indent2">Is it not? Just what [is the case]?” standing [thus],</l>
<l rend="indent3">a mirror<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">āṭi</term>: if we want to adopt the majority reading and take it literally, we have to read an elliptical metaphor: the countenance of the mother who has not yet spoken is as a mirror. Indeed it is very tempting to adopt the less well-attested variant <term xml:lang="ta">nāṭi</term>, "searching", the mother trying to read the mind of the daughter: "scrutinizing what is hidden with an intelligent strong mind".</note> of what is hidden by an intelligent(?) strong mind<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mati val uḷḷam</term>: here we see two designations of the mind in a row, <term xml:lang="ta">mati</term> usually rather referring to the intellectual component, <term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷam</term> (as <term xml:lang="ta">neñcam</term>) to the emotive or voluntative component. Perhaps it is best to take <term xml:lang="ta">mati</term> as an attribute of <term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷam</term> here.</note> –</l>
<l>as for you, it is necessary to consider [the situation]<note place="foot">Namely, the situation constituted by these three facts: the millet is ripe and either is or will be harvested, so SHE can no longer meet her lover there, the jasmine is already in bloom (whatever that may signify in this context), and the mother is suspicious, since she might or might not have heard rumours about secret meetings. As T.V.G. would say: time to arrange for the marriage.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">o you with flower-like eyes,
 <choice>  
<seg>the way it is appropriate.</seg>
<seg>because that is appropriate.</seg>
</choice></l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="11b">
    <l>the way it is appropriate for you with flower-like eyes.</l>
</lg>
